Task 1

Read Chapter 1-3 of Fundamentals of Data Visualizations, then answer the questions below.

Question 1.1

Describe the visualization concept scales.

Answer 1.1

Whenever we visualize data, we take data values and convert them in a systematic and logical way into the visual elements that make up the final graphic. Even though there are many different types of data visualizations, and on first glance a scatter plot, a pie chart, and a heatmap dont seem to have much in common, all these visualizations can be described with a common language that captures how data values are turned into blobs of ink on paper or colored pixels on screen. The key insight is the following: All data visualizations map data values into quantifiable features of the resulting graphic. We refer to these features as aesthetics. To map data values onto aesthetics, we need to specify which data values correspond to which specific aesthetics values. This mapping between data values and aesthetics values is created via scales. A scale defines a unique one - one mapping between data and aesthetics If a scale isnt one-to-one, then the data visualization becomes ambiguous.

Question 1.2

In Figures 2.3 and 2.4 the same data is visualized in two different ways. Discuss the pros and cons of the two approaches. Which one do you prefer and why?

Answer 1.2

Line graphs and heat maps are two different types of data visualizations that can be used to represent temperature data for four different places over the course of several months. Each has its own set of pros and cons:

line graph

Pros of line graph can be listed as(1)Clarity for Trends: Line graphs are excellent for showing trends over time. They make it easy to compare temperature variations over the months for different places. Viewers can quickly identify temperature fluctuations and patterns.(2)Individual Place Comparison: You can represent each place with a different colored line, allowing for straightforward visual comparison of temperature variations between the four locations. Cons:Limited Space: In a line graph, you might run out of space if you have many months or places to represent, making it less suitable for displaying extensive datasets.

Heat Map:

Pros:(1)Visual Overview: Heat maps provide a high-level visual overview of temperature patterns. They can quickly convey which months are warmer or cooler across the four places.(2)Color-Based Comparison: Colors can be used to represent temperature ranges, making it easy to compare temperature patterns visually. Viewers can quickly identify hotter and colder months across different places.(3)Compact Representation: Heat maps are space-efficient and can represent data for many months and locations in a relatively compact format. Cons:(1)Loss of Precision: Heat maps do not provide precise temperature values for individual months or places, so if precise values are crucial, they may not be the best choice.(2)Difficulty in Identifying Exact Values: It can be challenging to determine exact temperature values from a heat map, especially if the color scale is not clearly defined.(3)Less Suitable for Trends: Heat maps are not as effective as line graphs at showing trends over time, as they emphasize relative comparisons more than precise values. (4)Limited Annotative Capability: Heat maps may not provide much room for annotations or labels to explain specific temperature events or details.

In summary, the choice between a line graph and a heat map depends on your specific goals and the audience's needs. Line graphs are better for showing precise data and trends, while heat maps are more suitable for providing a visual overview of temperature patterns and comparisons. It's also possible to use both types of visualizations together to provide a comprehensive representation of the data.

Question 1.3

Describe situations when nonlinear axes might be useful. When should they not be used?

Answer 1.3

Nonlinear axes can be valuable tools for specific types of data, such as exponential or highly skewed datasets, where they can enhance visualization and interpretation. However, they should be used cautiously, with clear explanations and proper labeling, to avoid misinterpretation and ensure that the audience understands the scale transformation applied to the data.

Situations when Nonlinear Axes Might be Useful:

Exponential Data, Large Range of Values, Skewed Distributions, Multiplicative Processes.

Situations when Nonlinear Axes Should Not be Used:

Misleading Interpretation: Commonplace Data, Data Manipulation, Comparative Analysis.

Question 1.4

In which situations could a polar coordinate system be useful?

Answer 1.4

The polar coordinate system, we specify positions via an angle and a radial distance from the origin, and therefore the angle axis is circular Polar coordinates can be useful for data of a periodic nature, in the context of geospatial data, i.e., maps. Locations on the globe are specified by their longitude and latitude,Cyclical DataDirectional Data: For data that has directional components, such as wind patterns, compass data, or star positions in astronomy, a polar coordinate system provides an intuitive way to display and analyze these directional relationships. It allows you to visualize angles and magnitudes effectively,Circular Spatial Data,Relationships in 360 Degrees,Comparing Multiple Cycles,Emphasizing Relative Proportions,Aesthetic and Design Choices.

Briefly discuss the drawback with each approach (standard errors, boxplots, and violin plots).






















Error-Bar Plot:
Drawback: Error bars represent standard errors, assuming normal distribution. If your data is not normally distributed, or if there are outliers, standard errors may not accurately represent the variability.


Boxplot:
Drawback: Boxplots provide a summary of the distribution but may not capture the full shape of the data. They can hide details about the distribution, especially in the tails. Outliers may also be displayed as individual points, making them easily overlooked.


Violin Plot:
Drawback: While violin plots provide a more detailed view of the distribution, they might be complex for some audiences to interpret. The width of the plot at a given point does not correspond to the density of data points, and the shape can be influenced by the kernel density estimation method chosen.






















One of the drawbacks with a violin plot is that it can be hard to read summary statistics from it. Produce a violin plot visual here, where you have also drawn the median for each violin, as well as the data points.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Assuming you have loaded your data and structured it appropriately

# Filter the data for the years 2009 and 2010
filtered_data = weather_tidy_data[weather_tidy_data['year'].isin(['Temp2009', 'Temp2010'])]

# Create a violin plot with medians and data points
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.violinplot(x='month', y='Temprature', hue='year', data=filtered_data, inner='points', scale='width')

# Add median lines
medians = filtered_data.groupby(['month', 'year'])['Temprature'].median().reset_index()
for i, month in enumerate(filtered_data['month'].unique()):
    for year in ['Temp2009', 'Temp2010']:
        median_val = medians[(medians['month'] == month) & (medians['year'] == year)]['Temprature'].values[0]
        plt.plot([i + 0.2, i + 0.8], [median_val, median_val], color='black', linewidth=2)

# Add legend
plt.legend(title='Year', labels=['2009', '2010', 'Median'])

sns.despine()
plt.title('Temperature Distribution with Medians and Data Points for 2009 and 2010')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Temperature (C)')

# Show the plot
plt.show()
















































Briefly discuss how you could make it easy for the reader to understand that the line the visual represent the median.






















To make it easy for the reader to understand that the line in the violin plot represents the median, we can provide clear annotations and a descriptive legend. Here are some strategies:
(1)Add a legend explicitly stating that the line represents the median.
(2)Add a text annotation near the median line explaining that it represents the median temperature.
(3)Use a consistent style for the median line (e.g., color, thickness) to distinguish it from other elements in the plot. This helps in visually highlighting the median.
how to read a violin plot:
The width of the violin represents the data density at different temperature values. A wider section indicates higher density.
The shape of the violin shows the distribution of temperatures. It may have one or more peaks, reflecting modes or subgroups in the data.
Dots:Dots inside the violin plot represent individual data points. They give an idea about the spread and density of the data at specific temperature values.
Median Line:The line inside the violin plot represents the median temperature. It is the middle value when the data is sorted in ascending order.

Some people argue that visuals should be as minimal as possible. On the webpage you have a bad example of a minimalist way to plot the min, median, and max temperature of each month in 2009 and 2010 using the dataset in Question 3.2 (where you hopefully have filtered out daily temperatures for 2009 and 2010). # Insert code here library(ggplot2)

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, theme_minimal, labs

# Assuming your filtered data is stored in a DataFrame named 'weather_data'
# Make sure your DataFrame has columns: 'year', 'month', and 'Temperature'

# Calculate the minimum, median, and maximum values for each month and year
summary_data = weather_tidy_data.groupby(['year', 'month'])['Temprature'].agg(['min', 'median', 'max']).reset_index()

# Create the minimalistic visual
plot = (ggplot(summary_data, aes(x='month')) +
        geom_point(aes(y='min', color='year'), size=2) +
        geom_point(aes(y='median', color='year'), size=2) +
        geom_point(aes(y='max', color='year'), size=2) +
        labs(x='Month', y='Temperature') +
        theme_minimal()
       )

print(plot)

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, labs, theme_minimal, theme, element_text
import pandas as pd
import os

data = pd.DataFrame({
    'Rank': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
    'Title': ['Star Wars: The Last Jedi', 'Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle', 'Pitch Perfect 3', 'The Greatest Showman', 'Ferdinand'],
    'Weekendgross': [71565498, 36169328, 19928525, 8805843, 7316746]
})

pos = data["Title"].values[np.argsort(data["Weekendgross"])]

BASE_WIDTH = 8  # Width in inches
BASE_HEIGHT = 6  # Height in inches

# Create the 'Figs' directory if it doesn't exist
if not os.path.exists("Figs"):
    os.makedirs("Figs")

p = (ggplot(data, aes(x='Title', y='Weekendgross/1000000'))
     + geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#87CEEB")
     + labs(x="Title", y='Weekendgross (million USD)', title="")
     + scale_x_discrete(limits=pos[::-1])
     + theme_minimal()
     + theme(legend_position="none",
             axis_text_x=element_text(size=6, angle=0, hjust=1.5))  # Adjust size and angle here
)

p.save("Figs/Fix1.png", width=BASE_WIDTH, height=BASE_HEIGHT, dpi=300)

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, labs, theme_minimal, theme, element_text

    'Rank': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
    'Title': ['Star Wars: The Last Jedi', 'Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle', 'Pitch Perfect 3', 'The Greatest Showman', 'Ferdinand'],

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Your data
data = {
    'region': ['Stockholm', 'Gothenburg', 'Malmo', 'Rest_of_sweden', 'Stockholm', 'Gothenburg', 'Malmo', 'Rest_of_sweden',
               'Stockholm', 'Gothenburg', 'Malmo', 'Rest_of_sweden', 'Stockholm', 'Gothenburg', 'Malmo', 'Rest_of_sweden'],
    'number_marriages': [949, 481, 297, 2359, 1960, 681, 467, 3603, 1995, 710, 430, 3634, 1558, 611, 395, 3221],
    'year': [2020, 2020, 2020, 2020, 2015, 2015, 2015, 2015, 2010, 2010, 2010, 2010, 2005, 2005, 2005, 2005]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Set the style for the plot
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

df=pd.read_csv('mobile.csv')
fd= df[df['Year'].isin([2009, 2010, 2011])]

# Create a line plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Share', hue='OperatingSystem', data=fd, marker='o', markersize=8, linewidth=2)

# Add labels and title
plt.title('Mobile Operating System Market Share Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Market Share (%)')

# Show legend
plt.legend(title='Company', loc='best')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Remember to print the visual
















































By default plotnine places the legend for a visual to the right, or bottom depending on a theme. Do you think having a legend next to the visual is the best solution?






















The best placement for a legend in a plot depends on the specific context and the nature of the data.  It's important to consider factors such as the layout of your plot, the amount of data, and the overall design goals. Ultimately, the decision on legend placement should be based on what enhances the clarity and interpretability of the visual for your audience.In this context having legend next to visual is beneficial so that readers can understand abbout operating system at first glance itself.






















Question 4.5
In the lecture I provided data on European nations median lifespan. Now using the full dataset (on the webpage) provided on the webpage select a subset of countries and visualize i) life-expectancy across a timespan of your choice and ii) life expectancy in 2020. Provide a brief motivation for your choice of visual - and why your choice is readable.






















line plot
A line plot is a powerful and clear visualization choice for displaying the evolution of life expectancy over time, especially when dealing with a time series dataset involving multiple countries.


















In[]:






data4 = pd.read_csv("Life_tidy_full.csv")
# Select a subset of countries (you can replace this list with the countries you're interested in)
selected_countries = [ 'India', 'Ireland', 'Iran', 'Iraq', 'Iceland']

# Filter data for the selected countries
subset_data = data4[data4["country"].isin(selected_countries)]

# Filter the dataset for the selected countries and the time span 1989 to 2020
subset_data1 = subset_data[(subset_data['Year'] >= 1989) & (subset_data['Year'] <= 2020) & (subset_data['country'].isin(selected_countries))]

# Create a line plot for life expectancy across the selected time span
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for country in selected_countries:
    country_data = subset_data1[subset_data1['country'] == country]
    plt.plot(country_data['Year'], country_data['Life_expactancy'], label=country)

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')
plt.title('Life Expectancy Across Time (1989-2020)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

plt.show()
















































Bar plots
Bar plots are suitable for showing and comparing values of different categories or groups. In this case, we are comparing the life expectancy of different countries in the year 2020.


Clarity of comparison: Bar plots make it easy to compare values across different categories (countries in this case) at a glance. Each bar represents a country's life expectancy, and the lengths of the bars make comparisons straightforward.


Readability: Bar plots are generally easy to read and interpret, making them suitable for conveying information to a wide audience.


Emphasis on individual values: The use of text labels on top of each bar emphasizes the specific life expectancy values, providing additional information without the need for a separate legend.


















In[]:






# Select relevant data for 2020
data_2020 = subset_data[subset_data["Year"] == 2020]

# Sort the data for better readability (optional)
data_2020 = data_2020.sort_values(by="Life_expactancy", ascending=False)



# Create a bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(data_2020["country"], data_2020["Life_expactancy"], color='skyblue')
plt.title("Life Expectancy in 2020")
plt.xlabel("Country")
plt.ylabel("Life Expectancy (years)")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
for i, v in enumerate(data_2020['Life_expactancy']):
    plt.text(i, v, str(v), ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=12)

plt.show()
